710753f-a.text:
12th Avenue, at the N. E. corner of W. 34th Street and northeastward. Shown at the corner is a diner under the New York Central Railroad's elevated roadbed. View 2 is the area that adjoins this
to the north, showing the yards there.
Incidently this site was formerly the rear entrance to that V shaped row of structures that constituted the old Manhattan Market
of 1871. This was completely removed tn 1936.
August 24, 1940
Views 1,2
P. L. Sperr

712205f-b.text:
West 34th Street, east from a point east of Twelfth Avenue, showing this thoroughfare being carried by a steel ramp over the railroad yards. This, in conjunction with a similar arrangement for Eleventh Avenue, constituted a major feature in the rehabilitation of this area under the joint auspices of the City and the Company in the furtherance of the West Side Improvement Project. View 2 is closer to Eleventh Avenue, being photographed across same. Note the distinctive Empire State Building in the background of both views.

August 24, 1940
September 2, 1940.

P.L. Sperr
